   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The
                           Suspicious Husband</title></hi>].<note>"Remarks." <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title><title>The Suspicious Husband</title>; A
                              Comedy, In Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#HoadlyDrBenjamin"
                                 >Dr. Hoadly</ref>. As Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-6. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. XIII. <hi rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Love for Love</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Mourning Bride</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><ref target="people.html#Muhammad"
                           >Mahomet</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Tancred and
                              Sigismunda</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Suspicious
                              Husband</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and
                        Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged
                        at the <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Theatre Royal, Covent
                           Garden</ref> on February 12<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1747. Laura
                        DeWitt and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The
                           Criticism Archive</hi>.</note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>Whoever reads this play, and more especially, whoever sees it, will be astonished,
               that it was the only drama the author ever wrote.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#HoadlyDrBenjamin">Hoadly</ref> wrote another play, <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Tatlers</title></hi>, which was only performed
                  in 1797 and never published. He also co-authored a burlesque with his brother,
                     <ref target="people.html#HoadlyJohn">John Hoadly</ref>, entitled <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Contrast; or, A Tragical Comical Rehearsal of
                        Two Modern Plays, and the Tragedy of <ref target="people.html#Epaminondas"
                           >Epaminondas</ref></title></hi>. The work was performed three times in
                  1731, but it was poorly received, as it derided such prominent playwrights as <ref
                     target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakespeare</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#JonsonBen">Ben Jonson</ref>. The brothers never published
                  the play as per the request of their father, <ref
                     target="people.html#HoadlyBenjamin">Benjamin Hoadly</ref>.</note> It was too
               good a beginning to give an omen, that it would be also the end of his theatrical
               career. But the author had other employment; and though his taste allured him to
               write for the stage, his prudence and wisdom directed him, not to omit more serious,
               and, perhaps, more essential, occupation.</p>

            <p>The learned prelate, <ref target="people.html#HoadlyBenjamin">Hoadly</ref>, Bishop of
               Winchester, had two sons, <ref target="people.html#HoadlyDrBenjamin">Benjamin</ref>
               and <ref target="people.html#HoadlyJohn">John</ref>. The eldest was a Doctor of
               Physic, and physician to the <ref target="people.html#GeorgeIIKingofGreatBritain"
                  >king</ref>; the youngest, a Doctor of Divinity, and chaplain to <ref
                  target="people.html#FrederickPrinceofWales">Frederick, Prince of Wales</ref>. They
               both became eminent in their professions; yet, though they each pursued with vigour
               their graver studies, they were both devoted to the fascinating charms of the
                     drama.<note><ref target="people.html#HoadlyDrBenjamin">Benjamin Hoadly</ref>
                  was the physician to the households of <ref
                     target="people.html#GeorgeIIKingofGreatBritain">King George II</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#FrederickPrinceofWales">Prince Frederick</ref>. <ref
                     target="people.html#HoadlyJohn">John Hoadly</ref> became chaplain to <ref
                     target="people.html#FrederickPrinceofWales">Frederick</ref>'s household in 1735
                  and went on to gain several significant preferments.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#HoadlyDrBenjamin">Benjamin</ref>, the eldest, is the author
               of "<title>The Suspicious Husband</title>;" though it has been always supposed that
               he had the assistance of his brother, in its composition.<note>Scholars believe that
                     <ref target="people.html#HoadlyJohn">John Hoadly</ref> may have contributed to
                  the composition of <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Suspicious
                     Husband</title></hi>.</note></p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>The divine, even more than the physician, seems to have been enamoured of theatrical
               amusements; for he wrote many sacred and other plays, which were found in manuscript,
               on his decease; he had, besides, an intimate acquaintance with <ref
                  target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>, and took delight in having
               interludes and other stage productions acted at his country house, whenever he
               invited company.<note><ref target="people.html#HoadlyJohn">John Hoadly</ref> had an
                  extremely active social life and was known for hosting impromptu productions
                  involving his guests at his country estate. <ref target="people.html#HoadlyJohn"
                     >John</ref> held intimate acquaintance with prominent literary and theatrical
                  figures such as <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">David Garrick</ref>, <ref
                     target="people.html#FieldingHenry">Henry Fielding</ref>, <ref
                     target="people.html#HogarthWilliam">William Hogarth</ref>, and <ref
                     target="people.html#DodsleyRobert">Robert Dodsley</ref>. Upon his death he had
                  left several unpublished plays and poems in a manuscript.</note></p>

            <p>It is said, that the great <ref target="people.html#HogarthWilliam">Hogarth</ref>, on
               a visit to <ref target="people.html#HoadlyJohn">Dr. John Hoadly</ref>, having
               undertaken to perform a part in one of those exhibitions, showed such deficiency in a
               retentive memory, that, with all his applications, he could never learn one single
               speech by heart, so as to speak it perfectly. To atone for this dulness, he
               ornamented the playbills of the evening with characteristic figures, so excellent,
               they are still preserved, though not engraved, amongst other of the works of this
               celebrated artist.</p>

            <p>The present comedy appeared in 1747, when <ref target="people.html#HoadlyDrBenjamin"
                  >Benjamin</ref> was forty-two, <ref target="people.html#HoadlyJohn">John</ref>,
               thirty-eight years of age, and the <ref target="people.html#HoadlyBenjamin"
                  >bishop</ref>, their father, still living.<note>At the time of this play's first
                  performance, <ref target="people.html#HoadlyDrBenjamin">Benjamin</ref> was 41,
                     <ref target="people.html#HoadlyJohn">John</ref> was 35, and their father,
                  indeed, remained alive.</note> That venerable prelate appears to have laid no
               restriction upon his two sons' dramatic fervour: probably he had a conception, that
               theatric zeal might be less dangerous, both to themselves and the world, than
               polemical ardour. He found his own good books as liable to condemnation from the
               clergy, as the dramas of his children from the audience of a theatre; and whilst he
               was souring his temper, and the minds of those <pb n="5"/>churchmen, whom, by his
               controversial sermons and pamphlets he attacked, his two sons were employed in
               disposing half the town to brotherly love, by chasing away spleen, in the jocund
               attractions of this production.<note><ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs"
                     >Inchbald</ref> here references <ref target="people.html#HoadlyBenjamin"
                     >Benjamin Senior</ref>'s involvement in the Bangorian Controversy, which was
                  incited by his sermon "<title>The Nature of the Kingdom of Christ</title>." In
                  this sermon, drawing upon "<title>My kingdom is not of this world</title>" from
                     <ref target="people.html#SaintJohn">John</ref> 18:36, <ref
                     target="people.html#HoadlyBenjamin">Benjamin Senior</ref> argued that there was
                  no Biblical justification for church government, as Christ had not vested
                  authority in any earthly persons.</note></p>

            <p>This comedy was, from its very first performance, received with testimonies of high
               favour; nor has time reduced its credit with the public. Ranger is the pleasantest
               man of frolicsome propensity, that was ever introduced upon the stage; because,
               though he has numerous faults, he has not one flagrant vice; and the rest of the
               characters are perfectly natural, though somewhat insipid: but their want of spirit
               is fully recompensed by the abundance which is bestowed upon Ranger; for in the glow
               of his fire, every character which surrounds him receives an animating
                  warmth.<note>The plot of this play revolves around the misadventures of two
                  couples, Frankly and Clarinda and Bellamy and Jacintha, who is the ward of the
                  Strictlands, Mr. Strictland being the title character. Ranger, a classic rake
                  character and the part assumed by <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid"
                     >Garrick</ref>, is a resident of the Temple and friend of Bellamy whose antics
                  cause confusion yet ultimately provide resolution.</note></p>

            <p>Strictland is supposed to have a superiority to most of the other parts, by being
               placed all through the piece, under the influence of a tormenting passion&#8212;but
               of all the jealous husbands on the stage, from the ancient Kitely and Ford, down to
               the modern Sir John Restless, Strictland is the most tame and unimportant: nor has
               he, or his wife, any other claims upon the interest of their auditors, than what
               arise from their connexion with that support of the play&#8212;the volatile
                     Ranger.<note><ref target="people.html#JonsonBen">Ben Jonson</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Every Man in his Humour</title></hi> (1598) follows
                  Kitely, a cloth merchant who becomes increasingly paranoid that he is being
                  cuckolded by his wife. In <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                     Shakespeare</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Merry Wives of
                        Windsor</title></hi> (1597), Ford is the jealous husband of Mrs. Ford, who
                  is courted by <ref target="people.html#Falstaff">Sir John Falstaff</ref>. <ref
                     target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Arthur Murphy</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>All in the Wrong</title></hi> (1761) centers around
                  the mutual jealousy of Sir John and Lady Restless.</note></p>

            <p>Next to Ranger himself, his hat is the most important individual of the comedy. Here,
               incident <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw><pb n="6"/>makes
               characters, or at least makes the audience feel no want of them.</p>

            <p>Those who doubt the justice of certain eulogiums passed on <ref
                  target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>, in many parts he acted, still
               suppose he was very excellent in the part of Ranger; yet the comedy lives, though
                  <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> is no more.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
